Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

Guinea has put measures in place to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
For information on how to return to the UK from Guinea, see Return to the UK
Travel Restrictions and borders
On 23 March it was announced that Conakry Airport would be closed until further notice.
On 27 March the President announced a state of emergency, closing the borders.
Quarantine measures were in force when the airport was open and those passengers showing coronavirus symptoms were taken to a government quarantine facility.
Keep up to date with information from your tour operator, transport or accommodation provider on the impact on any existing travel plans. If you need further information about entry requirements, contact the local immigration authorities or the nearest Guinean Embassy. You should also check with your airline or travel company for the latest information.
Local measures
The President has declared a state of emergency until 15 May.
There is a limit of 20 people assembling for marriage, baptism and funeral services. Schools and mosques are closed, as well as bars.
On 30 March the President announced a curfew from 9pm to 5am. There is a ban on movement from Conakry to other parts of the country.
Medical Care
If you have any health concerns relating to coronavirus, call the local government helpline l’Agence Nationale de Securité Santé (ANSS) 629 995 656 / 626 069 797. Information on coronavirus is also on the government website www.anss-guinea.org.
Those testing positive for coronavirus must remain at the government coronavirus health centre.
From 18 April everyone must wear a mask and those not wearing masks will be liable to pay a fine of 30,000 GNF.
Further information
Given the rapidly changing situation in Guinea we have temporarily withdrawn a limited number of UK staff and their dependents from the British Embassy. The Embassy will continue to carry out essential work including providing 24/7 consular assistance and support to British people in Guinea.
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
